Quantitative Genetics – PCB6555

Covariance Between Relatives

Felipe Ferrão and Marcio Resende Jr

University of Florida – October, 2020

Recapping:

  • We initially expressed genotypic means, breeding value and genotypic variance as a function of allele frequencies and genotypic values.
  • We expressed the variances in terms of additivity (\(V_A\)) and dominance (\(V_D\)).
  • In the sequence, we expressed the variances in terms of resemblance between relatives by computing covariances.

Plan for today:

  • Knowing the relationship of a given population and using experimental statistics we can finally have access to the causal variance components (\(V_A\) and \(V_D\)).
  • This can be done using classical ANOVA or via mixed model.
  • Introduction to asreml-r package

1 Theory

1.1 Introduction

In the last topic we derived the equations for calculating the total genetic variance and the additive and dominance components. This section shows how the variance within or covariance between relatives can be used to, in practice, estimate the the additive and dominance portion of the genotypic variance. Given the importance of connecting theory with practice, resemblance between relatives has been treated as the central dogma of the quantitative genetics and can be used to estimate genetic components in a given population.

RA Fisher (1918).Transactions of the Royal Society of Edinburgh 52: 399-433

1.2 Resemblance between relatives

The covariance between two random variables is a measure of how much they vary together— covary.

For example, if the covariance is large and positive, they tend to vary in the same way. On the other hand, if the covariance is small, it means there isn’t a strong tendency for deviations from the mean in one variable to be associated with deviations in the other.

\[Cov(X,Y) = \sum p_{xy} (x_i-\mu_x) (y_i-\mu_y)\]

There are different ways to calculate the covariance between relative. Below, a summary of expected covariance in genotypic values between groups of relatives and how to compute the covariance between relatives using covariance properties or the general method:

1.2.1 Summary

Relatives Covariance in genotypic values
Offspring \(x\) - One parent \(y\) 1/2 Va
Half siblings 1/4 Va
Full siblings 1/2 Va + 1/4Vd
Nephew \(x\) - Uncle \(y\) 1/4 Va
First cousins 1/8 Va
Monozygotic twins Va + Vd

1.2.2 Covariance

Deriving this covariance relies on a mathematical property of the covariance. Specifically, we can expand the covariance equation according to genotypic means and show how is the resemble between parent and offspring:

Parent Offspring
Genotype Freq Genotypic Value A1A1 A1A2 A2A2 Mean Value Mean Value - Pop.Mean
A1A1 \(p^2\) \(2q-(\alpha - qd)\) p q - \(pa -qd\) \(q\alpha\)
A1A2 2pq \((q-p)\alpha + 2pqd\) p/2 1/2 q/2 \(1/2[a(p-q)+d]\) \(1/2(q-p) \alpha\)
A2A2 \(q^2\) \(-2p( α + pd)\) - p q \(pd-qa\) \(-p\alpha\)

where Pop.Mean = \(a(p-1)+2pqd\)

Assuming that all values are centered on the mean, the covariance equation can be simplified as: \(Cov(X,Y) = \sum p_{xy} (x_iy_i)\) and the covariance between a parent and the offspring can be computed with a bit of algebra:

\[\begin{align*} COV(P,O) = p^2 [2q(\alpha-qd).q\alpha] + 2pq[(q-p) \alpha + 2pqd] . [1/2(q-p) \alpha] + q^2 [-2p(\alpha + pd) . (-p\alpha)]\\ = 2p^2 q^2 \alpha^2 - 2p^2 q^3 d\alpha + pq^3 \alpha^2 - p^2 q^2 \alpha^2 - p^2 q^2 \alpha^2 + p^3 q\alpha^2 + 2p^2 q^3 d\alpha - 2p^3 q^2 d\alpha + 2p^2 q^2 \alpha^2 + 2p^3 q^2 d\alpha\\ = pq^3 \alpha^2 + p^3 q \alpha^2 + 2p^2 q^2 \alpha^2\\ = pq\alpha^2 (q^2 + p^2 + 2pq)\\ = pq\alpha^2 \\ = \dfrac{1}{2} V_A\\ \end{align*}\]

Same logic can be used for full and half-siblings families

1.2.3 General Method

The expected covariance in genotypic values in pedigrees can also be computed using the general method, as proposed by Cotterman (1974,1983) and Crow and Kimura (1970); by separating the additive and dominance variances

\[Cov(X,Y) = rV_A + uV_D\]

\[Cov(X,Y) = 2\theta_{XY}V_A + \Delta_{xy}V_D\]

where:

  • r = \(2f_{xy}\) or \(2\theta_{XY}\). The \(r\) coefficient is twice the probability that individuals x and y inherit an allele that is identical by descent. The \(r\) is also called the coefficient of relationship or kinship or coancestry and can be seen as the correlation between the breeding values. We discussed about this during our first class when the COANCESTRY software was presented.

  • u = \(f_{AC}f_{BD}+f_{AD}f_{BC}\) or \(\Delta_{xy}\). The \(u\) coefficient is the probability that individuals x and y inherit the same genotype. The probability of inheriting the same genotype depends on the probability that both alleles in the genotypes of \(x\) and \(y\) are identical by descent. This is why the \(u\) term is not null when covariance between full-sibs is considered – in a full-sib family, there is a probability of one-quarter of all sib-pairs have the same genotype.

Example of full-sib

Hamilton, (2009)

1.3 Conclusion

  • We know how to partition the variances (ANOVA)
  • We also know how to design progeny tests (breeding)
  • We can combine both information to estimate genetic parameters

2 Practice

2.1 Classical ANOVA

2.1.1 Numerical Example

  1. Create an experimental desing using family structure
  2. Estimate the variance components using the Method of Moments
  3. From the knowledge of the relationship between kinship, from the results of ANOVA, it is possible to estimate \(V_A\) and \(h^2\).

Nested paternal half-sibling design

Diagram of a nested paternal half-sibling design. Conner and Hartl, (2009)

ANOVA table

Source d.f. Mean square Composition
Among sires \(s-1\) \(MS_s\) \(\sigma^2_W + k\sigma^2_D + dk\sigma^2_s\)
Among dams (within sires) \(s(d-1)\) \(MS_D\) \(\sigma^2_W + k\sigma^2_D\)
Within progenies \(sd(k-1)\) \(MS_W\) \(\sigma^2_W\)

\[V_A = 4\sigma^2_S\] \[V_D = 4(\sigma^2_D-\sigma^2_S)\] \[V_E = \sigma^2_W- 3\sigma^2_D + \sigma^2_S \] \[h^2 = \dfrac{4\sigma^2_S}{\sigma^2_S + \sigma^2_D + \sigma^2_W}\]

Numerical Example

  • Example from from Falconer and Mackay.
  • 719 offspring from 74 sires and 192 dams, each with one litter.
Source d.f. Mean square Composition
Among sires 70 17.10 \(\sigma^2_W + k'\sigma^2_D + dk'\sigma^2_s\)
Among dams (within sires) 118 10.79 \(\sigma^2_W + k\sigma^2_D\)
Within progenies 527 2.19 \(\sigma^2_W\)

d = 2.33; k=3.48 ; k’= 4.16

  • \(\sigma^2_W = MS_W = 2.19\)
  • \(\sigma^2_D = (1/k) (MS_D - \sigma^2_W) = 2.47\)
  • \(\sigma^2_S = (1/dk') (MS_S - \sigma^2_W - k'\sigma^2_D) =0.48\)

Thus,

  • \(V_P = \sigma^2_S + \sigma^2_D + \sigma^2_W = 5.14\)
  • \(V_A = 4 \sigma^2_S = 1.92\)
  • \(h^2 = \dfrac{V_A}{V_P} = 0.37\)

2.1.2 Theory

Mate a number of males (sires) with a number of females (dams). Each sire is mated to more than one dam, but each dam mates only with one sire. This design is called nested paternal half-sibling design:

Diagram of a nested paternal half-sibling design. Conner and Hartl, (2009)

We can perform an ANOVA on the phenotype in the progeny, treating sire and dam as main effects. The offspring of each dam represent full-sibling families (because they have the same mother and father), and these are nested within half-sibling families, that is, all the offspring of the same father. The variance among half-sibling families can be used to estimate \(V_A\).

Source d.f. Mean square Composition
Among sires \(s-1\) \(MS_s\) \(\sigma^2_W + k\sigma^2_D + dk\sigma^2_s\)
Among dams (within sires) \(s(d-1)\) \(MS_D\) \(\sigma^2_W + k\sigma^2_D\)
Within progenies \(sd(k-1)\) \(MS_W\) \(\sigma^2_W\)

Now we need some way to relate the variance components (\(\sigma^2_W, \sigma^2_D, \sigma^2_S\))to \(V_A\), \(V_D\), and \(V_E\). This could be done using the results from the resemblance between relatives. for example:

\[V_P = \sigma^2_{total} = \sigma^2_S + \sigma^2_D + \sigma^2_W\] where \(\sigma^2_S\) estimates the variance among the means of the half-sib familes fathered by each of the different sires or, equivalently, the covariance among half-sib or

\[\sigma^2_S = Cov_{HS} = \dfrac{1}{4}V_A\] In the sequence, we can consider the within progeny component of the variance, \(\sigma^2_W\). In general, it can be shown that any among group variance component is equal to the covariance among the members within the groups. Thus, a within group component of the variance is equal to the total variance minus the covariance within groups. In this case,

\[\begin{align*} \sigma^2_W= V_P - Cov_{FS}\\ = V_A + V_D + V_E -[1/2 V_A + 1/4 V_D]\\ = \dfrac{1}{2} V_A + \dfrac{3}{4} V_D + V_E \\ \end{align*}\]

From here, it remains only \(\sigma^2_D\). Now, \(\sigma^2_W = V_P - Cov_{FS}\), \(\sigma^2_S = Cov_{HS}\) and \(\sigma^2_T=V_P\). Thus,

\[\begin{align*} \sigma^2_D= \sigma^2_T - \sigma^2_S - \sigma^2_W \\ = V_P - Cov_{HS} - (V_P - Cov_{FS})\\ = Cov_{FS} - Cov_{HS} \\ = [1/2 V_A + 1/4 V_D] - 1/4 V_A\\ = \dfrac{1}{4} V_A + \dfrac{1}{4} V_D\\ \end{align*}\]

So if we rearrange these equations, we can express the genetic components of the pheno- typic variance, the causal components of variance, as simple functions of the observational components of variance:

\[V_A = 4\sigma^2_S\] \[V_D = 4(\sigma^2_D-\sigma^2_S)\] \[V_E = \sigma^2_W- 3\sigma^2_D + \sigma^2_S \]

\[h^2 = \dfrac{4\sigma^2_S}{\sigma^2_S + \sigma^2_D + \sigma^2_W}\]

2.2 Mixed Model in R

  • Half-sib model
  • Full-sib model
  • Clonal model
  • asreml-r package

2.2.1 Half-sib Model

  • There are multiple ways to estimate variance components and breeding values from progeny test data.
  • In some cases, we might be interested in parental breeding values.
  • Parental models based on half-sibs (also called GCA model) may be preferred, because it it is straightforward to fit.
  • We need to solve a mixed model equation for the parents and not for the offspring.

2.2.1.1 Example

  • Download the OPENPOL.txt file
    • Description: a tree genetic study consisting on seeds from a total of 28 female parents were collected from mass selection and tested in a RCBD. The experiment consisted in 10 replicates with 34 plots each of size 2 x 3. The response variables of interest are total height (HT, cm) and diameter at breast height (DBH, cm).
Effect Observation Levels
INDIV progenies ID 2040
REP block effect 10
PLOT 34 plot nested in 10 blocks 340
FEMALE 28 females + 3 controls 31
TYPE test + control (checks) 2
HT total height (HT, cm) numeric

The objective is to rank the female parents for future selections and seed production. Note that a model can be fitted with and without the controls included as parents.

2.2.1.2 Postulating a Mixed Model

\[y_{ijk} = \mu + B_i + \underline{F_j} + \underline{BF_{ij}} + \underline{e_{ijk}}\]

  • \(\mu\) is the overall mean;
  • \(B_i\) = effect of block i
  • \(F_j\) = random effect of female j, where \(F_{j} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_g)\)
  • \(BF_{ij}\) = random effect of interaction between block i and female j (this is the plot effect), where \(BF_{ij} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_{b \times g})\)
  • \(e_{ijk}\) = random effect error, distributed as: \(e_{ijk} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_e)\)

OBS: depending on the experimental desing the linea model can change. In this case, we have multiple female observation per plot within block, therefore we could test the interaction (or create a explicit plot effect in the model). In the case of single-tree plots (for example, when an average value per plot is measured) we should drop the “plot effect” from the model.

asreml-R codes

library(asreml)

###############################
## Sire Model (Female) 
###############################
# Download the factor
openp<-read.table("/home/lferrao/Dropbox/classes/2020/QuantitativeGenetics/week7/OPENPOLs.txt", h=T)
head(openp)
table(openp$FEMALE,openp$REP) # complete blocks, but multiple information per block, for this reason we have the plot effect

# Factors
openp$INDIV = factor(openp$INDIV)
openp$REP<-as.factor(openp$REP)
openp$FEMALE<-as.factor(openp$FEMALE)
openp$PLOT<-as.factor(openp$PLOT)
openp$TYPE<-as.factor(openp$TYPE)
str(openp)

# Some EDA
hist(openp$HT)
table(openp$REP, openp$FEMALE)

# Fitting Sire/Female model
# y = m + block + !female + !plot %in% block + !e
mF<-asreml(fixed=HT~REP,
           random=~FEMALE+PLOT,
           data=openp)
plot(mF)
summary(mF)$varcomp

# Same model in lme4
#mF1 = lmer(HT ~REP + (1|FEMALE) + (1|PLOT), data=openp)
#summary(mF)

# Inference Fixed Effect
wald.asreml(mF) # More similar to the regular anova

# Inference Random Effects
BLUP = summary(mF,coef=TRUE)$coef.random
BLUE = summary(mF,coef=TRUE)$coef.fixed
adj.mean = predict(mF,classify='FEMALE')$pvals # adjusted mean (original scale)

library(dplyr)
adj.mean %>%
  arrange(desc(predicted.value)) %>%
  head()

# Additive h2
vpredict(mF,h2~4*V1/(V1+V2+V3))

###############################
## Sire Model + Checks 
###############################

# Question:
# i. Checks are fixed or random effects? 
# ii. What is the importance to use checks?
# iii. When do we use checks? 

# Fitting female model separating controls
levels(openp$TYPE)
mFAT<-asreml(fixed=HT~REP+at(TYPE,'Control'):FEMALE,
           random=~at(TYPE,'Test'):FEMALE+PLOT,
           data=openp)
plot(mFAT)

# Goodness-of-fit
library(asremlPlus)
infoCriteria(mF)
infoCriteria(mFAT)

# Inference fixed effect
wald.asreml(mFAT,denDF='algebraic')

# Inference random effect
summary(mFAT)$varcomp # similar 
preds<-predict(mFAT,classify="TYPE:FEMALE")$pvals
preds %>%
  arrange(desc(predicted.value)) %>%
  head()

# H2
vpredict(mFAT,h2~4*V1/(V1+V2+V3))

2.2.2 Full-sib Model

  • Full-sib models can be used to estimate additive and dominance effects.
  • A classical way to estimate such variances is by defining an individual’s phenotype as a linear combination of the parental general combining ability (GCA) – which are function of the additive variance – and a linear combination of the family effec – called specific combining ability (SCA), that results from allelic interactions within a loci.
  • In this case, we might estimate parental breeding values and family effects.
  • More details on that when we discuss about diallels and mating desings.

2.2.2.1 Example

  • Download the CONTPOL.txt file
    • Description: A total of 177 families and 8 checklots were planted in a test using a RCBD with 25 blocks. For all families planted both parents are known.
Effect Observation Levels
FAMILY 173 regular families + 9 controls 182
REP block effect 25
MALE male information 57
FEMALE female information 54
YIELD production numeric

The objective is to rank the parents and the best families for the YIELD trait. Note that a model can be fitted with and without the controls.

2.2.2.2 Postulating a Mixed Model

\[y_{ijk} = \mu + B_i + \underline{G_j} + \underline{G_k} + \underline{S_{jk}} + \underline{e_{ijk}}\]

  • \(\mu\) is the overall mean;
  • \(B_i\) = effect of block i
  • \(G_j\) = random effect of female j, where \(G_{j} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_f)\)
  • \(G_k\) = random effect of male k, where \(G_{i} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_m)\)
  • \(S_{jk}\) = random effect of family jk, where \(S_{jk} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_f)\)
  • \(e_{ijk}\) = random effect error, distributed as: \(e_{ijk} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_e)\)

OBS: a similar model is also presented in diallel analysis, where the parental effects is called general combining ability (GCA) and the family effect is called specific combining ability (SCA)

asreml-R codes

library(asreml)

###############################
## Full sib 
###############################

# Download the data 
fs<-read.table("/home/lferrao/Dropbox/classes/2020/QuantitativeGenetics/week7/CONTPOL.txt", h=T)
head(fs)

table(fs$FAMILY,fs$REP) # complete block desing
table(fs$MALE, fs$FEMALE) # partial diallel

# Factors
fs$REP<-as.factor(fs$REP)
fs$FEMALE<-as.factor(fs$FEMALE)
fs$MALE<-as.factor(fs$MALE)
fs$FAMILY<-as.factor(fs$FAMILY)

# Analysis Full-Sib - Two additive terms
FSIB<-asreml(fixed=YIELD~REP,
             random=~FEMALE+MALE+FAMILY,data=fs)
summary(FSIB)$varcomp

# Select the parentes
pred.MALE<-predict(FSIB,classify="MALE",sed=TRUE)$pvals
pred.FEMALE<-predict(FSIB,classify="FEMALE",sed=TRUE)$pvals

# Ranking
pred.FEMALE %>%
  arrange(desc(predicted.value)) %>%
  head()

pred.MALE %>%
  arrange(desc(predicted.value)) %>%
  head()

# h2
vpredict(FSIB,h2~ 2*(V1+V2)/(V1+V2+V3 +V4)) # additive
vpredict(FSIB,h2~4*(V3)/(V1+V2+V3 +V4)) # dominance

# i) Dominance effect seems more important that additive? Why?

2.2.3 Clonal Model

  • In some species, individuals can be cloned.
  • Cloning individuals for within family-selections is common in the breeding context of some perennial crops.
  • Among the main advantages, cloning desings allows breeders to i) capture non-additive genetic effects among and within crosses; ii) increase the accuracy of genotypic values predictions, since more replications are considered.

2.2.3.1 Example

  • Download the CLONES.txt file
    • Description: A clonal test derived from a total of 61 families crossed in a circular mating design were established in a field trial with 3 repetitions and incomplete blocks desing. Each family has several clones.
Effect Observation Levels
FamilyID full-sib families 61
IncBlock Incomplete blocks 110
Rep rep within incomplete blocks 3
Male male information (no pedigree) 26
Female female information (no pedigree) 27
VOL volume numeric

The objective of this study is to estimate all variance components (additive, dominance and epistasis).

2.2.3.2 Postulating a Mixed Model

\[y_{ijk} = \mu + B_j + \underline{G_j} + \underline{G_k} + \underline{S_{jk}} + \underline{T_{ijk}} + \underline{e_{ijk}}\]

  • \(\mu\) is the overall mean;
  • \(B_i\) = effect of incomplete block i
  • \(G_j\) = random effect of female j, where \(G_{j} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_f)\)
  • \(G_k\) = random effect of male k, where \(G_{i} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_m)\)
  • \(S_{jk}\) = random effect of family jk, where \(S_{jk} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_f)\)
  • \(T_{ijk}\) = random effect of the clone ijk, where \(T_{ijk} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_f)\)
  • \(e_{ijk}\) = random effect error, distributed as: \(e_{ijk} \sim N(0, I\sigma^2_e)\)

asreml-R codes

library(asreml)

###############################
## Clonal Models + Incomplete Blocks 
###############################

# Download
clonal<-read.table("/home/lferrao/Dropbox/classes/2020/QuantitativeGenetics/week7/CLONES.txt",h=T)

# Complex experimental design
# Incomplete block designs, because each block does not contain a complete set of treatments.
# More information: chapter 8, Galwey (2006)
table(clonal$IncBlock,clonal$FamilyID) # Incomplete block desing
table(clonal$cloneid,clonal$IncBlock) # clones of a given plant randomized across the blocks

# Factors
head(clonal)
clonal$Rep<-as.factor(clonal$Rep)  
clonal$IncBlock<-as.factor(clonal$IncBlock)
clonal$Female<-as.factor(clonal$Female)
clonal$Male<-as.factor(clonal$Male)
clonal$FamilyID<-as.factor(clonal$FamilyID)
clonal$cloneid<-as.factor(clonal$cloneid)
str(clonal)

# Fitting Full Clonal Model - single Female & Male
clonalf<-asreml(fixed=VOL~Rep,
              random=~Rep:IncBlock+Female+Male+FamilyID+cloneid,
              data=clonal)
summary(clonalf)$varcomp
plot(clonalf)

(H2 = vpredict(clonalf,H2~(V1+V2+V3+V5)/(V1+V2+V3+V4+V5+V6))) # total
(h2 = vpredict(clonalf,h2~2*(V1+V2)/(V1+V2+V3+V4+V5+V6))) # additive
(d2 = vpredict(clonalf,d2~4*V3/(V1+V2+V3+V4+V5+V6))) # dominance
(i2 = vpredict(clonalf,i2~(V5-V1-V2-3*V3)/(V1+V2+V3+V4+V5+V6))) # non-additive

3 Final conclusions

In this section, we show how the components of variance in a population can be estimated from previous knowledge of the resemblance between relatives and the use of experimental statistics. Traditionally, we first showed it by investigating classical ANOVA examples via the decomposition of the variance components. In the sequence, we presented three common plant breeding designs (half-sibs, full-sibs, and clonal model) and estimated additive and dominance variances using mixed models. For the next class, we will see how similar analyses can take advantage of pedigree information indexing the genotypic random effects.
